### Preserving Digital Pathways: The Imperative of Link Integrity

The most critical function of a redirect from a page move is to maintain [link integrity](/Help:Link). As the explanatory note explicitly states, "This page was kept as a redirect to avoid breaking links, both internal and external, that may have been made to the old page name." This isn't merely a courtesy; it's a fundamental requirement for any interconnected information system.

Consider the ripple effect of a broken link. Internally, countless other Wikipedia articles might have referenced the original page name. If that page simply vanished or stopped existing, every one of those internal links would become a dead end, a digital void where information once flowed. This would degrade the user experience, undermine the interconnectivity that defines Wikipedia, and create a cascade of necessary, painstaking manual corrections. Externally, websites, academic papers, news articles, or even personal bookmarks might have linked to the old page name. If those external links were to suddenly cease functioning, it would sever connections to external resources, frustrating users and diminishing Wikipedia's reputation as a reliable reference.

Therefore, the old page name is not simply abandoned; it is repurposed. It becomes a permanent waypoint, a historical marker that ensures continuity. It's a silent guardian against the entropy of information, ensuring that even as knowledge evolves and its presentation is refined, the pathways to that knowledge remain intact. The existence of this redirect, leading to the comprehensive [List of busiest airports by passenger traffic](/List_of_busiest_airports_by_passenger_traffic), is a quiet testament to the meticulous, often unseen, effort that goes into making the vast repository of Wikipedia accessible and reliable. It’s a mechanism that, while seemingly trivial, underpins the entire edifice of interconnected information, ensuring that no link is ever truly lost, merely rerouted.